about.title: About Us
about.content:
About Us

  1. Home
  2. About Us

Foster Bros. Marine was created in January 2007. But our story starts way before that date! How far back do you want to go? Let's start at what I perceive as the real beginning. A guy by the name of Hank Mullen was a working at Crosstown Marine back in the late 70's and through the mid 80's.  If you purchased a Sea Ray boat in that era, there's good odds you bought it from Hank. In 1986 Hank ventured out on his own and started Mullen Marine Brokerage. As the next few years went by, he moved from place to place, finally ending up in Delano, MN. He was mainly brokering used boats but also picked up a couple of new product lines: DAKA Docks and Triton trailers.  

In 1994, Stuart Foster purchased a used boat from Hank Mullen. This is where Mark Foster enters the story. At that same time, Mark was looking for a part-time job and began working for Hank. He didn't know it at the time but that part-time gig would end up defining a large part of his life! He ended up working at Mullen Marine every summer throughout college and full time for a year and ½ afterward. During this time, Hank added a new line of pontoons called GillGetter which is now known as Qwest Pontoons. In November of 2001, Mark left Mullen Marine to pursue a marketing career in Minneapolis.

Throughout this same time period, the late 90's and early 2000's, Brian Foster worked for a variety of marine business in the area before stepping out on his own. By 2005, he had more boats around his house than he knew what to do with and was looking for a garage to rent.

Fast forward to 2006. Hank put his business up for sale. Brian and Mark teamed up to buy Mullen Marine Brokerage in April of 2006. Mark brought his marketing and sales background. Brian brought his mechanics and service background. We hit the ground running and haven't looked back.

Milestones for Foster Bros. Marine

  • April 2006, purchased Mullen Marine, an existing Qwest Dealer.  
  • In January 2007, changed the name to Foster Bros. Marine. 
  • 2008 – Became a certified Honda Marine Dealer
  • 2010 – Became a Porta Dock Dealer
  • 2012 – Became a certified Mercury Dealer
  • 2013 moved to our current facility - a 22,000 Sq. ft.  floorplan w/ a large showroom & multiple service bays
  • 2014 – Became a StarCraft Pontoon Dealer
  • 2015 – Became a KingFisher Boat Dealer
  • 2019 – Became a Skeeter Dealer
  • 2019 – Became a certified Yamaha Dealer
  • 2020 – Became a SeaArk Dealer
  • 2020 – Became a Bass Cat & YarCraft Dealer

PONTOONS & BOATS: We are here to help you get into the boat, motor or trailer that will best fit your needs.  Whether you’re looking for the right pontoon or aluminum or fiberglass fishing boat, we’ll spend the time get you into the one that fits your needs the best.  

INVENTORY: Our new and used inventory is always changing. Check out our Inventory page for our current stock of pontoons, fishing boats, runabouts, motors and trailers.

PARTS & ACCESSORIES: We stock a large selection of both. If we don't have it on hand most parts can be here in one or two business days. We are always looking to stock the newest products to keep your boat on the cutting edge.  

AUTHORZED SERVICE CENTER:  Our service department is a certified Mercury, Yamaha and Honda warranty center. We work on most brands of outboards and I/O's.  Call in to make an appointment or ask us any question you might have.  

OUR CUSTOMERS:  We know individuality is important, which is why we pay close attention to the interests of each customer. From the minute you walk through the door, meeting your needs is our top priority. Founded not only on excellent customer service, but also on the principles of hard work and a focused attitude, this is why Foster Bros. Marine has a long list of satisfied customers. Call or stop by; you’ll be glad you did.

blog-post-1.title: 5 Tips For Proper Trailer Maintenance
blog-post-1.content:
1. Home
  2. Blog

Back to Blog Posts

5 Tips For Proper Trailer Maintenance

December 2, 2024 | Service Tips | By: Mark Foster

In the 18 Years we’ve been in business, one trait most boat owners seem to have in common is neglecting their trailers!  I don’t think it’s an intentional neglect but more an effect of not thinking about it or simply not knowing what to even look at.  We came up with an essential list of trailer maintenance items for you.    

1.  How To Maintain Boat Trailer Tires 

This one is easy.  Very simply, take the time to look at your tires.  Most tire issues are visually noticeable when inspected.  Running your hand over the tire can also help find improper wear issues or even metal belts sticking out of the rubber.  

  • Make sure the tire pressure is properly set per the tire specifications.  Don’t be overinflated or underinflated.  
  • Added Note –  If your tire is removed from your trailer, make sure you check the lug nuts between 50 and 100 miles to ensure they are still properly tightened.  

 

2.  Trailer Light Troubleshooting & Inspection Tips

We’ve spent more time in our shop parking lot helping customers with trailer lights than I’d like to remember!!  Since the world has gone to LED lights, this issue has VASTLY improved.  That being said there are still a ton of issues.  In our experience there are two main causes of your trailer lights not working.

  • Vehicle –  This first issue to look at is making sure the vehicle is sending proper signals to the trailer.  If this isn’t happening, the trailer obviously will not work.   Start by checking the connections between the vehicle and trailer, the 7-to-4 or 7-to-5 adapter if you use one, and of course the fuses of the vehicle
  • If there is one main cause of the trailer itself, it would a ground issue.  Start by making sure the trailer is properly grounded by tightening the ground wire connection, removing any rust or debris, or even re-splicing into the old wire.  From there, move on to other connections in the system.  

 

3.  Bearing Maintenance & Grease Tips  

When the topic of trailer maintenance has come up over the year, the most common question that we’ve been asked is “What kind of grease should I use?”  The basic answer is just make sure it gets changed periodically.  That being said, there are reasons to use Marine Grade Grease and other higher-end, more expensive greases.  Our service department uses Marine Grade Grease.  

  • Marine Grade will have higher water-resistant properties.  
  • Lithium Grade will perform better in higher heat situation
  • Calcium Sulfonate Grade has higher corrosion resistant properties which can be helpful in Saltwater conditions.  

 

4.  Trailer Brakes Knowledge  

Always pay attention to how your trailer performs when towing.  As you pull up to a stop, you should feel the trailer assist in slowing the vehicle down.  If this is not happening, consult a mechanic quickly as this can be a safety issue!

  • Brake Fluid – a quick tip is to make sure you check the fluid level if your trailer has hydraulic brakes.  

 

5.  Inspect Your Trailer  

We have seen some pretty extreme cases come through our shop over the years.  The one that comes to mind first is crossmember that was literally rusted almost completely through!!  So, we’re hoping most us won’t let the neglect get that far but here are some common things to look for.  

  • Missing safely pin –  All trailer couplers are designed to use a safety pin as added protection to keep the trailer safety connected to the vehicle.  Make sure you have one and use one.  
  • Brake safety cable –  If your trailer has brakes, there will be a safety strap with a hook.  This is designed to connect to the tow vehicle, not the safety chains, and activate the brakes in case the trailer accidentally comes off the hitch in transit.  
  • Worn strap and tie downs:  Inspect straps and hooks.  If they are frayed or cut, replace them.  These items are cheap!  
  • Tires & Lights – as mentioned above, keep an eye on these usable parts and make sure they are in good condition and working order.  

We could probably go on and on about this topic and if you start paying a little more attention to your trailer maintenance you might just avoid a breakdown on the road.  Let’s face it, nobody wants to be that guy!  If you have any questions or concern about your trailer, please contact your local mechanic or call our service team.

 

See you on the water!

Foster Bros. Marine

blog-post-2.title: Top Tips For How To Purchase The Right Boat at a Show
blog-post-2.content:
1. Home
  2. Blog

Back to Blog Posts

Top Tips For How To Purchase The Right Boat at a Show

January 13, 2025 | Boat Show | By: Mark Foster

Top Tips for Smart Boat Show Purchases: How to Choose the Perfect Boat or Pontoon

Boat Show season is around the corner and without question it is a great time to purchase a boat or pontoon.   Dealers and manufacturers are hungry to kick the new selling season off with a bang.  At the show, you’ll find discounted dealer pricing as well as many manufacture discounts.  Most of these have an expiration date on them that you will want to be prepared for.  

One of the greatest things about a boat show is also one of the worst – the number of boats you have to look at under one roof is amazing.  It’s great to be able to compare brands but it’s also very easy to get completely overwhelmed at the options.  I can tell you countless stories of couples showing up Saturday morning with the intent to research, inspect and buy a pontoon.  They stop back at the booth later that afternoon completely exhausted and confused – most of them go home feeling further away from a decision than when they started the day.   

If you have the ability to do a little research prior to the show and narrow your options down to 6 or less options, that will save you a lot of time, stress & confusion.  It will be a lot easier to compare a few boats than literally hundreds.  Choosing a layout or design can be one of the most challenging.  

Top 5 tips to choosing the best boat layout for you

Notice in the header I added “for you.”  That’s because you need to find the right design for how you spend your time.  While I could likely ramble on about this topic with tip after tip, I narrowed it down to the top 5 for choosing a layout.   Here are some questions and comments I still make at boat shows today.  

  • “What does your day on the water look like?’  This is always one of the first questions I ask perspective buyers about a layout or design.  I recommend picturing yourself on the water for a typical day and sit in the boat.  You’ll be able to narrow down the layouts to a manageable number pretty quickly by eliminating the ones you don’t like first.   You can then start deciding which ones you like better.  
  • “Don’t But a boat for July 4th”.   This is another statement you’ll here me say at a boat show no less then 1,000 times.   If you typically boat with 4 to 6 people you do not need a 25’ boat.  Just because you have a family gathering once a year doesn’t mean you need a boat that everyone can fit in.  What will happen is you end up using the boat less throughout the year because it is less convenient – the cover is too much work to remove, the boat is too large to pull up to the dock, maintenance costs are higher, etc.  
  • “Don’t over think it”.  While you absolutely want to make sure you don’t pick a bad layout, there is also no need to scrutinize the minor details.  I have had multiple conversations with people about the smallest of details that will have absolutely zero impact to their day on water.  If table location, button size, door location etc. doesn’t seem perfect, don’t sweat it.  After you start using the boat, these minor details will likely simply disappear.  
  • “What Horsepower engine should I get?”  This has always been the hardest question for me to answer because the best answer is “it depends.”  My job is to best determine what your day on the water looks like and suggest the engine that you will be most satisfied with.  In some cases it comes down to a safety concern – the larger the lake, the larger the HP I’ll suggest.  The more watersports, for example, you want to do, the higher the HP you’ll need.
  • “If you are on the fence, go bigger.”  If you are deciding between a 60 HP or 75, go bigger.  If you are deciding between a 19’ and 20’, go bigger.  While there are definite reasons you stay smaller, most boaters know about “two-foot-itis” As soon as you get a boat, you want a bigger one!   You will very likely not be disappointed in the decision to go bigger.  

Top 4 tips to consider when choosing a dealership

Most people get pretty excited about the shiny new boat they sometimes forget about who they buy from can also make a big difference.  

  • Comfort Level -  Are you comfortable with them from the start?  If you have an uncomfortable feeling to begin with, you may want to go with you gut and shop elsewhere.
  • Service – this is all to often overlooked.  When boating, there is always a need for service.  Whether you need to deal with an unfortunate warranty issue, wanting to add accessories or needing to store your boat, an experienced service shop is essential.
  • Experience – Has the dealer been around for a long time?  Is the product you’re purchasing newer on the market or has it been around?  
  • Location – this can also be consideration.  The closer the dealer is to your lake, the more convenient any service or advice you need will be to get.  

I hope this helps you come up with a game plan and gives you a better buying experience.  Our goal in selling you a boat or pontoon is to get you into the best product the maximize your enjoyment on the water.  

 

See you on the water!

Foster Bros. Marine
